## Vercel Web Analytics Installation Complete

Successfully installed and configured Vercel Web Analytics for this Next.js App Router project.

### Changes Made

**1. Package Installation**
- Installed `@vercel/analytics@^2.0.1` using npm
- Updated package.json and package-lock.json with the new dependency

**2. Analytics Integration**
- Modified `/app/layout.tsx` to add Vercel Analytics
- Added import: `import { Analytics } from "@vercel/analytics/next";`
- Added `<Analytics />` component at the end of the body element (after RegisterSW component)

### Implementation Details

Following the official Vercel Analytics documentation (https://vercel.com/docs/analytics/quickstart), the Analytics component was integrated into the root layout for Next.js App Router:

- **Framework**: Next.js 16.2.6 (App Router)
- **Package Manager**: npm
- **Integration Location**: `/app/layout.tsx` (root layout)
- **Component Placement**: End of body element, ensuring it loads after all main content

The Analytics component is now properly integrated and will automatically track page views and web vitals when deployed to Vercel with Analytics enabled in the dashboard.

### Files Modified

1. **app/layout.tsx** - Added Analytics import and component
2. **package.json** - Added @vercel/analytics dependency
3. **package-lock.json** - Updated lockfile with new dependency tree

### Next Steps

To enable analytics data collection:
1. Deploy this application to Vercel
2. Enable Web Analytics in the Vercel dashboard under your project's Analytics tab
3. After deployment, analytics will automatically begin tracking page views and web vitals

### Notes

- The Analytics component is placed at the end of the body to ensure it doesn't block critical rendering
- The integration follows Vercel's best practices for Next.js App Router
- No additional configuration is required; analytics work out of the box when enabled in Vercel dashboard
- Pre-existing build errors in the codebase (missing components in settings pages) are unrelated to this change
